        <title>Pettiagalla O.P. Ceylon</title>
        <published>2010-03-15T00:00:00+00:00</published>
        <updated>2010-03-15T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
        
        <author>
          <name>
            Josh Fairhead
          </name>
        </author>
        
        <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="https://joshafairhead.com/tea-blog/pettiagalla-op-ceylon/"/>
        <id>https://joshafairhead.com/tea-blog/pettiagalla-op-ceylon/</id>
        
        <content type="html" xml:base="https://joshafairhead.com/tea-blog/pettiagalla-op-ceylon/">&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https:&#x2F;&#x2F;joshafairhead.com&#x2F;tea-blog&#x2F;pettiagalla-op-ceylon&#x2F;image1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Pettiagalla Op Ceylon packet&quot; &#x2F;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;https:&#x2F;&#x2F;joshafairhead.com&#x2F;tea-blog&#x2F;pettiagalla-op-ceylon&#x2F;image2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Tea close-up&quot; &#x2F;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;https:&#x2F;&#x2F;joshafairhead.com&#x2F;tea-blog&#x2F;pettiagalla-op-ceylon&#x2F;image3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Tea brewed tea&quot; &#x2F;&gt;
This is some bloody good tea…
It tastes very fruity in a good way, although orange in the title is a reference to dutch royalty rather than the taste; however it seems to actually have a really subtle background taste of orange in it. Its similar to a typical darjeeling with its texture but has a bit more body. Some what of a medium weight tea and a new favorite for the moment.
“If god had dandruff it would be these tea leaves” - Darren Jennings (my flatmate)&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&quot;tea-details&quot;&gt;Tea Details&lt;&#x2F;h2&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Price:&lt;&#x2F;strong&gt; £6 (before 25% discount)&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Grade:&lt;&#x2F;strong&gt; O.P. (Orange Pekoe)&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;ul&gt;
</content>
        
